a purchasing power parity paradox siepr siepr stanford institute for economic policy research search the site enter your keywords main links home about siepr research at siepr education at siepr events at siepr people at siepr publications at siepr economics in the news support siepr contact us stay connected stay connected banner home publications profile display a purchasing power parity paradox type siepr discussion paper 00 025 author s asaf zussman published 01 1 01 download pdf abstract the balassa samuelson hypothesis is considered the most important structural model of long run deviations from purchasing power parity ppp i present a simple model that builds on the balassa samuelson hypothesis and in which paradoxically ppp necessarily holds in the long run in this model real exchange rates converge because productivity levels converge the model's predictions are tested empirically for 24 oecd countries in the period 1950 92 overall the analysis supports the prediction that productivity convergence is accompanied by real exchange rate convergence stanford university economics department stanford center for international development public policy program site map economic summit
